  "text": "The LLVM IR type system flows from creation to code generation through several interconnected layers:\n\n## Type Creation and Hierarchy (IR Level)\n\nThe base `Type` class is defined in `llvm/include/llvm/IR/Type.h` (line 45). All types inherit from this class and maintain a reference to their owning `LLVMContext` (line 83). Derived types are defined in `llvm/include/llvm/IR/DerivedTypes.h`:\n\n- **IntegerType** (line 42): Represents arbitrary-width integer types, created via `IntegerType::get(LLVMContext&, unsigned)` static factory method\n- **FunctionType** (line 105): Represents function signatures with return type and parameters\n- **StructType** (line 218): Represents aggregate types with named or literal layouts\n\nThese types use uniquing: only one instance of each type exists within a context, enforced through static factory methods.\n\n## Context Ownership and Type Storage\n\nThe `LLVMContext` class (`llvm/include/llvm/IR/LLVMContext.h`) acts as a container for global state including type uniquing tables. The actual implementation is in `LLVMContextImpl` (`llvm/lib/IR/LLVMContextImpl.h`, line 1620).\n\nKey type storage structures in LLVMContextImpl:\n- `IntegerTypes` (DenseMap, line 1759): Maps bit-width to IntegerType*\n- `FunctionTypes` (DenseSet with FunctionTypeKeyInfo, line 1762): Uniquely stores function types\n- `AnonStructTypes` (DenseSet with AnonStructTypeKeyInfo, line 1764): Stores literal struct types\n- `NamedStructTypes` (StringMap, line 1765): Maps names to identified struct types\n- `TargetExtTypes` (DenseSet, line 1769): Stores target-specific extension types\n- Primitive type instances (line 1747-1750): VoidTy, LabelTy, FloatTy, DoubleTy, IntegerTypes for i1, i8, i16, i32, i64, i128\n\n## IR to Machine Type Conversion\n\nThe conversion from LLVM IR types to machine types happens in the instruction selection phase:\n\n**SelectionDAGBuilder** (`llvm/lib/CodeGen/SelectionDAG/SelectionDAGBuilder.h/cpp`) translates IR instructions to the SelectionDAG intermediate representation. It converts LLVM IR types to Extended Value Types (EVT).\n\n**Extended Value Types (EVT)** are defined in `llvm/include/llvm/CodeGen/ValueTypes.h` (line 35). EVT can represent:\n- Simple machine value types (MVT) like i32, f64, v4i32\n- Extended types for non-standard sizes like i12345\n\nKey EVT factory methods:\n- `EVT::getIntegerVT(LLVMContext&, unsigned)` (line 65): Creates integer types\n- `EVT::getVectorVT(...)` (lines 74-88): Creates vector types\n\n## Type Legalization in SelectionDAG\n\nAfter building the DAG from IR, the **DAGTypeLegalizer** (`llvm/lib/CodeGen/SelectionDAG/LegalizeTypes.h`, line 31) transforms the DAG to only contain legal types for the target.\n\nKey legalization methods:\n- `DAGTypeLegalizer::getTypeAction(EVT)` (LegalizeTypes.h, line 62): Queries `TargetLowering::getTypeAction()` to determine if a type is:\n  - `TypeLegal`: Already legal, no transformation needed\n  - `TypePromoteInteger`: Promote to a larger type\n  - `TypeExpandInteger`: Split into smaller types\n  - `TypeSoftPromoteHalf`: Convert to integer representation\n  - `TypeScalarizeVector`: Convert vector to scalar\n  - `TypeSplitVector`: Split vector into smaller vectors\n  - `TypeWidenVector`: Widen vector to larger size\n\n- `DAGTypeLegalizer::run()` (LegalizeTypes.cpp, line 9): Main entry point performing top-down DAG traversal\n\nInternal transformation maps in DAGTypeLegalizer track the mapping of illegal values to their legal replacements:\n- `PromotedIntegers`: Maps promoted integer values\n- `ExpandedIntegers`: Maps expanded (split) integer values\n- `SoftenedFloats`: Maps float values converted to integers\n- `SplitVectors`: Maps split vector values\n- `WidenedVectors`: Maps widened vector values\n\n## Type Action Determination\n\nThe **TargetLowering** class (`llvm/include/llvm/CodeGen/TargetLowering.h`) defines which types are legal on the target and how illegal types should be handled. The critical method is:\n\n- `TargetLowering::getTypeAction(LLVMContext&, EVT)` (line 1153): Returns the legalization action for a given type on this target\n\nThis creates the connection between IR types (via EVT) and target-specific legalization decisions, enabling the SelectionDAG to generate code for types that the target machine supports.\n\n## Data Flow Summary\n\n1. **IR Types** are created via Type class hierarchy and stored in LLVMContextImpl type tables\n2. **SelectionDAGBuilder** converts IR to SelectionDAG, translating Type* to EVT\n3. **DAGTypeLegalizer** analyzes EVTs via TargetLowering::getTypeAction()\n4. **Legal types** are selected based on target capabilities, transforming the DAG as needed\n5. **Code generation** proceeds with only target-legal types in the DAG"
